Even if you don’t like wings, come check out Wangs. This is a takeout dream— moist chicken, creamy mac and cheese, and delightful fusion of southern cooking and Asian flavor.

The wings are in my top 10. If I had to be honest normally when I get these I like to go someplace private. Just so that I don’t scare anyone as I devour these wings. The other items are really good but it’s all about the wings for me. They’ve got nice spice not greasy. Just crispy fried goodness.

This is some GOOD chicken! Had the chicken sandwich, slaw, mac n cheese, and whole chicken. EVERYTHING was amazing. LOVED the wonderful combo of flavors on the chicken sandwich. The only complaint I could possibly have is a couple bites of the whole fried chicken was a little too salty. The spicy sauce and garlic ginger aoili was soooo good. Oh and the cornbread was good too! It was moist and a little sweet. To drink we tried the blueberry hibiscus which i didn't like because it was unsweetened (my husband didn't tell me that lol). Surprisingly I liked the peach and cardamom tea. I don't even like cardamom. It had a little sweetness to it. I would definitely recommend this place!

Wangs has nailed the way an outdoor eatery ought to be. What is there not to love about Wangs if you are in the mood for a chicken meal! Serving a variety of house items such as the popcorn chx or fried chx sandwich, there is also a wonderful selection of healthy side dishes such as collard greens or kimchi. The summer special corn on the cob with a topping of sesame sauce, spices and lime was delicious. I loved the unsweetened iced hibiscus lemon tea, a perfect thirst quencher for the hot NYC summer weather.

I really wanted to like this place, but the only thing that is worth getting here are the actual “wings”. They are seasoned, huge, crispy and the sauce is great and flavorful. Everything else absolutely SUCKS. I guess it’s what I get from expecting any kind of good “soul food” to come out of park slope. The sides are absolutely disgusting, shameful and do not deserve to be in the category of “soul food”. Macaroni is unflavored, no butter, milk and hardly a speck of cheese with dry unseasoned bread dust on top. Cornbread is dry as hell and granulated left over feeling in your mouth. Collards watery and dreadful. It’s like they did not study actual soul food cooking or spend time eating lots of it. And if the plan was to make it more “healthy” then you should not be modeling the menu off of soul food in the first place. We put lots of flavor in our food and we marinate it for hours and we use butter and fat!  This place is about the wings and they did a great job, but I still can’t get past the disgraceful side options. If I come back it will only be for the wings.

I live in Park Slope and ordered a ridiculously overpriced dinner from Wangs for my family this evening.  First, it took over an hour.  When my order arrived, the popcorn chicken was overcooked, dry, hard as hell, and cold; the chicken sandwich was cold and cooked too hard, and they forgot to include one of my sides (potato salad).  I immediately contacted the restaurant as soon as the driver left and asked them to bring my order of potato salad.  A guy replies, "I'm sorry, we can give you a refund.  The driver is on his way to deliver a catering order."  I retort, "He just left, so why can't he circle back, pick-up the potato salad, and bring it to me?  I'm 4 blocks away."  A manager takes the phone and says, "I'm sorry, we can bring you the potato salad later or give you a refund."  Newsflash: my family was in the midst of eating after waiting an hour!  I am DONE with this place and will not be ordering from this hole-in-the-wall ever again.  They need to bring the falafel restaurant back, or this place needs to step its customer service game up.  I can care less if you have one driver.  The fact that you negligently left my side order out and had the audacity to staple the bag solidifies your incompetence and ignorance.  Gnarly Eats has a much better chicken sandwich anyway.  I'll be calling Grubhub to get a FULL refund and I'll be cutting and pasting this true story wherever food ratings live.

Quite literally a hole in the wall, with an order window and picnic tables outside, Wangs does its name justice and then some. I stopped by this restaurant while in the area for an appointment nearby. I had been craving down home southern style food but I thought I'd give this place a try - soul food with a twist. The cashier at the window seemed pretty friendly and helpful while I placed my order. This spot is pretty much a take out place but there are some tables and benches outside. Honestly, I ordered way to much food but there was so much I wanted to try. I ordered half a fried chicken with potato salad, collard greens and cornbread. Getting the food home was difficult because I was so curious and everything smelled great. But once I got home to try the food my excitement faded a little I must admit. First, I'll start with what I thought was the best part of the meal - the cornbread. It was excellent and cake like but not sweet like typical southern style cornbread. The scallion butter was the perfect finishing touch but I would've preferred if it was served separately. By the time I got home the butter was all over and came through the bag the bread was in. The collard greens were delicious but in my opinion had to much of the sausage in one serving. The potato salad was very different but good however, it was hard for me not to compare it to what I'm used. It lacked the flavor that I'm used to in its traditional version. I had high expectations for the chicken but when I tried the breast - which is my favorite part - it was undercooked and the batter was still gooey in some areas. This is a definite issue that needs to be resolved. I had planned to try their wings at another time but after this experience I'm not sure about a repeat visit because the prices are pretty high.
